<subSubSection pageId="99" pageNumber="99" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="99.[128,654,1318,1759]" pageId="99" pageNumber="99">
COMMENTS: In the original description, Rothschild noted that he had an adult male, the type, and a juvenile male. The 
<typeStatus box="[526,629,1588,1609]" pageId="99" pageNumber="99">paratype</typeStatus>
is 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[128,308,1617,1638]" pageId="99" pageNumber="99">AMNH 302363</emphasis>
, immature male, collected on Mount Kunupi, 
<quantity box="[334,427,1647,1669]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.2" pageId="99" pageNumber="99" unit="m" value="1200.0">1200 m</quantity>
, on 
<date pageId="99" pageNumber="99" value="1931-09-19">19 September 1931</date>
by Stein (no. 2921).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="99.[128,654,1318,1759]" pageId="99" pageNumber="99">
From DNA sequencing, 
<bibRefCitation author="Nunn and Cracraft" firstAuthor="Nunn" pageId="99" pageNumber="99" pagination="445 - 459" refId="ref132318" refString="Nunn, G. B., and J. Cracraft. 1996. Phylogenetic relationships among the major lineages of the birds-of-paradise (Paradisaeidae) using mitochondrial DNA gene sequences. Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution 5 (3): 445 - 459." type="journal article" year="1996">Nunn and Cracraft (1996)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Irestedt" box="[337,587,1737,1759]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Irestedt" pageId="99" pageNumber="99" pagination="235" refId="ref127262" refString="Irestedt, M., K. A. Jonsson, J. Fjeldsa, L. Christidis, and P. G. P. Ericson. 2009. An unexpectedly long history of sexual selection in birds-ofparadise. BMC Evolutionary Biology 9: e 235." type="journal article" year="2009">Irestedt et al. (2009)</bibRefCitation>
have
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="99.[701,1228,214,622]" pageId="99" pageNumber="99">
shown that 
<taxonomicName authorityName="P.L.Sclater" authorityYear="1873" box="[840,980,213,234]" class="Aves" family="Paradisaeidae" genus="Drepanornis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="99" pageNumber="99" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[840,980,213,234]" italics="true" pageId="99" pageNumber="99">Drepanornis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is not closely related to other sickle-billed birds of paradise, genus 
<taxonomicName box="[701,824,271,294]" class="Aves" family="Paradisaeidae" genus="Epimachus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="99" pageNumber="99" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[701,824,271,294]" italics="true" pageId="99" pageNumber="99">Epimachus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Most authors have synonymized 
<emphasis box="[701,791,303,324]" italics="true" pageId="99" pageNumber="99">inversus</emphasis>
with 
<taxonomicName box="[856,1140,301,324]" class="Aves" family="Paradisaeidae" genus="Drepanornis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="99" pageNumber="99" phylum="Chordata" rank="subSpecies" species="albertisi" subSpecies="cervinicaudus">
<emphasis box="[856,1140,301,324]" italics="true" pageId="99" pageNumber="99">D. albertisi cervinicaudus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, except 
<bibRefCitation author="Cracraft" box="[701,985,332,354]" firstAuthor="Cracraft" page="17 - 18" pageId="99" pageNumber="99" pagination="1 - 43" refId="ref121493" refString="Cracraft, J. 1992. The species of the birds-ofparadise (Paradisaeidae): applying the phylogenetic species concept to a complex pattern of diversification. Cladistics 8: 1 - 43." type="journal article" year="1992">Cracraft (1992: 17–18)</bibRefCitation>
, who synonymized 
<emphasis box="[701,791,362,383]" italics="true" pageId="99" pageNumber="99">inversus</emphasis>
with 
<taxonomicName authority="albertisi" box="[869,1106,361,384]" class="Aves" family="Paradisaeidae" genus="Drepanornis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="99" pageNumber="99" phylum="Chordata" rank="subSpecies" species="albertisi" subSpecies="albertisi">
<emphasis box="[869,1106,361,384]" italics="true" pageId="99" pageNumber="99">D. albertisi albertisi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and considered 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="P.L.Sclater" baseAuthorityYear="1873" box="[793,921,390,413]" class="Aves" family="Paradisaeidae" genus="Drepanornis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="99" pageNumber="99" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="albertisi">
<emphasis box="[793,921,390,413]" italics="true" pageId="99" pageNumber="99">D. albertisi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
a phylogenetic species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="99.[701,1228,214,622]" pageId="99" pageNumber="99">
Mount Kunupi is shown on the map in 
<bibRefCitation author="Hartert" box="[701,1027,451,473]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Hartert" page="168" pageId="99" pageNumber="99" pagination="165 - 240" refId="ref126298" refString="Hartert, E., K. Paludan, Lord Rothschild, and E. Stresemann. 1936. Die Vogel des Weyland- Gebirges und seines Vorlandes. Mitteilungen aus dem Zoologisches Museum in Berlin 21: 165 - 240." type="journal article" year="1936">Hartert et al. (1936: 168)</bibRefCitation>
, on the middle Menoo River, a tributary of the Wanggar River, which enters southern Geelvink 
<collectingRegion box="[1175,1224,511,532]" country="Somalia" name="Bay" pageId="99" pageNumber="99">Bay</collectingRegion>
. 
<bibRefCitation author="Stein" box="[701,966,540,562]" firstAuthor="Stein" page="289 - 306" pageId="99" pageNumber="99" pagination="253 - 310" refId="ref137014" refString="Stein, G. [H. W.]. 1933. Eine Forschungsreise nach Niederlandisch-Ostindien. Journal fur Ornithologie 81: 253 - 310." type="journal article" year="1933">Stein (1933: 289–306)</bibRefCitation>
described this camp and (
<bibRefCitation author="Stein" box="[762,938,570,592]" firstAuthor="Stein" page="26" pageId="99" pageNumber="99" pagination="21 - 57" refId="ref137041" refString="Stein, G. H. W. 1936. Ornithologische Ergebnisse der Expedition Stein 1931 - 1932. V. Beitrage zur Biologie Papuanischer Vogel. Journal fur Ornithologie 84: 21 - 57." type="journal article" year="1936">Stein, 1936: 26</bibRefCitation>
) published notes on this species.
</paragraph>
